                "name": "John Madinger",
                "href": "/profile/John-Madinger"
            },
            "answer_text": "I never worked patrol, so I can\u2019t comment for them, but we did take calls, people asking for a response regarding some drug activity. Always wrote something, although a lot of times it was classified as an intelligence report, no enforcement action. If we got called for a pharmacy robbery or burglary, prescription fraud, or a complaint involving a registrant (someone authorized to prescribe, dispense, or administer controlled substances) those got written up for the record. Investigations generate phenomenal amounts of paperwork. People have no idea how paper-intensive the job is, and it has to be perfect, because sooner or later, the defense attorney is going to see it, and if there are mistakes, he\u2019s going to beat you over the head with them for as long as he can and love every minute of it. And you\u2019ve got to account for your time, your car, official property signed out to you, your buy money, money paid to informants, evidence, etc, etc. It wasn\u2019t unusual to work on a case for 24 hours straight, and then spend another 12 doing paperwork. That\u2019s what I tell people asking about careers in law enforcement. You\u2019d better be a good writer and be comfortable filling out government forms, because that\u2019s about half your life. ",
