                "name": "Martin Shirilla",
                "href": "/profile/Martin-Shirilla-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "No, they don't. Not every call requires a written report. Mandatory reports are for crimes and arrests that meet the National Incident Based Repirt System (NIBRS), which are (supposed to be) submitted by all U. S. law enforcement agencies. But calls for service also include things like disabled motorist, well - being checks, suspicious person (activity found to involve no crime), traffic crashes, traffic control, shots fired ( we get LOTS of those calls during hunting season - callers bought the house in the spring and were ignorant about deer hunting), 911 disconnect calls (but dialed cell phones, crappy landlines when it rains), domestic arguments ( verbal only), and a host of other complaints that don't involve crimes \u201cbut ought to be a crime\" according to the complainant. Most of these calls are \u201clogged\" with a short comment in the dispatch log (e-records), while some officers keep notes in steno pads or similar notepads. ",
